tuals, and mythologies meant to recast the meaning of the cosmos and create new transcendent and immanent black bodies whose meaning cannot be reduced to products of racism. Whether examining how the myth of Yakub helped Elijah Muhammad explain the violence directed at black bodies, how Malcolm X made black bodies in the NOI publicly visible, or the ways Farrakhan’s discourses on his experiences with the Mother Wheel UFO organize his interpretation of black bodies, Finley demonstrates that the NOI intended to retrieve, reclaim, and reform black bodies in a context of antiblack violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAfrican American MuslimsxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxReligionxHistory. 0aBlack peoplezAmericaxReligionxHistory. 0aIslamzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMuslimszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023418?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023418/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles